# URL to the S3 CSV file
data_source <- "https://s3.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/msds.ds.6306.2/CaseStudy2-data.csv"

# Read the CSV file from S3
data <- read_csv(data_source, show_col_types = FALSE)
data_numeric <- data # creating copy of dataset to convert to all numeric

# Check for missing values
missing_values <- any(is.na(data$DailyRate) | is.na(data$Attrition))

# Check for non-finite values
non_finite_values <- any(!is.finite(data$DailyRate) | !is.finite(data$Attrition))

# drop columns that have only one value - not relevant
data_numeric <- data_numeric[, -which(names(data_numeric) == "Over18")]
data_numeric <- data_numeric[, -which(names(data_numeric) == "EmployeeCount")]
data_numeric <- data_numeric[, -which(names(data_numeric) == "StandardHours")]

# Factor data into categorical data
data_numeric$Attrition <- factor(data_numeric$Attrition)
data_numeric$BusinessTravel <- factor(data_numeric$BusinessTravel)
data_numeric$OverTime <- factor(data_numeric$OverTime)

label_mapping <- c("No"=0, "Yes"=1)
data_numeric$Attrition <- label_mapping[data_numeric$Attrition]

label_mapping <- c("Non-Travel"=0, "Travel_Rarely"=1, "Travel_Frequently"=2)
data_numeric$BusinessTravel <- label_mapping[data_numeric$BusinessTravel]

label_mapping <- c("No"=0, "Yes"=1)
data_numeric$OverTime <- label_mapping[data_numeric$OverTime]

label_mapping <- c("Human Resources"=1, "Research & Development"=2, "Sales"=3)
data_numeric$Department <- label_mapping[data_numeric$Department]

label_mapping <- c("Human Resources"=1, "Life Sciences"=2, "Marketing"=3, "Medical"=4, "Other"=5, "Technical Degree"=6)
data_numeric$EducationField <- label_mapping[data_numeric$EducationField]

label_mapping <- c("Male"=1, "Female"=2)
data_numeric$Gender <- label_mapping[data_numeric$Gender]

label_mapping <- c("Healthcare Representative"=1, "Human Resources"=2, "Laboratory Technician"=3, "Manager"=4, "Manufacturing Director"=5, "Research Director"=6, "Research Scientist"=7, "Sales Executive"=8, "Sales Representative"=9)
data_numeric$JobRole <- label_mapping[data_numeric$JobRole]

label_mapping <- c("Divorced"=1, "Married"=2, "Single"=3)
data_numeric$MaritalStatus <- label_mapping[data$MaritalStatus]

model1 <- naiveBayes(data_numeric[, c("OverTime", "MaritalStatus", "JobInvolvement")], data_numeric$Attrition)

# Create Train and Test datasets
set.seed(4)
trainIndices = sample(seq(1:length(data_numeric$ID)),round(.7*length(data_numeric$ID)))
trainData = data_numeric[trainIndices,]
testData = data_numeric[-trainIndices,]

# Train a Naive Bayes model on the training set
model1 <- naiveBayes(trainData[, c("OverTime", "MaritalStatus", "JobInvolvement")], trainData$Attrition)
model2 <- naiveBayes(trainData[, c("TotalWorkingYears", "JobLevel", "YearsInCurrentRole")], trainData$Attrition)
model3 <- naiveBayes(trainData[, c("OverTime", "MaritalStatus", "JobInvolvement","TotalWorkingYears", "JobLevel", "YearsInCurrentRole")], trainData$Attrition)

# Make predictions against the test dataset
predictions1 <- predict(model1, newdata = testData)
predictions2 <- predict(model2, newdata = testData)
predictions3 <- predict(model3, newdata = testData)

# Create confusion_matrix to get accuracy, sensitivity and specificity
confusion_matrix1 <- table(Actual = testData$Attrition, Predicted = predictions1)
confusion_matrix2 <- table(Actual = testData$Attrition, Predicted = predictions2)
confusion_matrix3 <- table(Actual = testData$Attrition, Predicted = predictions3)

# Calculate accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity for model1
accuracy1 <- (confusion_matrix1[1, 1] + confusion_matrix1[2, 2]) / sum(confusion_matrix1)
sensitivity1 <- confusion_matrix1[2, 2] / sum(confusion_matrix1[2, ])
specificity1 <- confusion_matrix1[1, 1] / sum(confusion_matrix1[1, ])

# Calculate accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity for model2
accuracy2 <- (confusion_matrix2[1, 1] + confusion_matrix2[2, 2]) / sum(confusion_matrix2)
sensitivity2 <- confusion_matrix2[2, 2] / sum(confusion_matrix2[2, ])
specificity2 <- confusion_matrix2[1, 1] / sum(confusion_matrix2[1, ])

# Calculate accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity for model3
accuracy3 <- (confusion_matrix3[1, 1] + confusion_matrix3[2, 2]) / sum(confusion_matrix3)
sensitivity3 <- confusion_matrix3[2, 2] / sum(confusion_matrix3[2, ])
specificity3 <- confusion_matrix3[1, 1] / sum(confusion_matrix3[1, ])

## Alter code to loop 100 times with a random seed value

# Set number of repetitions
num_repetitions <- 100

# Create variables
accuracy_values <- numeric(num_repetitions)
sensitivity_values <- numeric(num_repetitions)
specificity_values <- numeric(num_repetitions)
F1_values <- numeric(num_repetitions)
RMSE_values <- numeric(num_repetitions)

# Perform the loop for different seeds
for (i in 1:num_repetitions) {
  
  # Split the data into training and test datasets
  set.seed(i)
  trainIndices <- sample(seq_len(nrow(data_numeric)), round(0.7 * nrow(data_numeric)))
  trainData <- data_numeric[trainIndices, ]
  testData <- data_numeric[-trainIndices, ]
  
  # Train a Naive Bayes model on the training set and make predictions against the test dataset
  model <- naiveBayes(trainData[, c("OverTime", "MaritalStatus", "JobInvolvement","TotalWorkingYears", "JobLevel", "YearsInCurrentRole")], trainData$Attrition)
predictions <- predict(model, newdata = testData, type = "raw")

if(is.factor(predictions)) {
    # Convert factor to numeric
    predictions <- as.numeric(as.character(predictions3))
}

  # Apply a threshold
  new_threshold = 0.20
  predicted_classes <- ifelse(predictions[, 2] > new_threshold, "Positive", "Negative")
  
  # Create a confusion_matrix to get accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity
confusion_matrix = table(Actual = testData$Attrition, Predicted = predicted_classes)

  
  # Calculate accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity and save the results
  accuracy <- (confusion_matrix[1, 1] + confusion_matrix[2, 2]) / sum(confusion_matrix)
  sensitivity <- confusion_matrix[2, 2] / sum(confusion_matrix[2, ])
  specificity <- confusion_matrix[1, 1] / sum(confusion_matrix[1, ])
  TP <- confusion_matrix[2, "Positive"]
  FP <- confusion_matrix[1, "Positive"]
  FN <- confusion_matrix[2, "Negative"]
  precision <- TP / (TP + FP)
  recall <- TP / (TP +FN)
  F1 <- 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)
  residuals <- testData$Attrition - predictions[, 2]  
  F1_values[i] <- F1
  accuracy_values[i] <- accuracy
  sensitivity_values[i] <- sensitivity
  specificity_values[i] <- specificity
  RMSE_values[i] <- sqrt(mean(residuals^2))
  

}

# Calculate the average of accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity
average_accuracy <- mean(accuracy_values)
average_sensitivity <- mean(sensitivity_values)
average_specificity <- mean(specificity_values)
average_F1 <- mean(F1_values)
average_RMSE <- mean(RMSE_values)

  theme_minimal()
